WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.600
Hey, I'm Kelly, I'm the product manager for a product here we sell commercially called

00:00:06.600 --> 00:00:07.600
Posit Connect.

00:00:07.600 --> 00:00:11.720
So, if you don't use Posit Connect or you never intend to, I'm sorry about this talk.

00:00:11.720 --> 00:00:17.120
Hopefully you can find my exaggerated use of hand gestures as I speak entertaining enough

00:00:17.120 --> 00:00:18.959
to stay in the audience.

00:00:18.959 --> 00:00:24.959
I want to give you here three exciting announcements we have in relation to event automation in

00:00:24.959 --> 00:00:31.360
Connect, which is something that I've desperately wanted to talk about for a very long time.

00:00:31.360 --> 00:00:38.000
And I'll start by positing that there are times when a document is better than an app.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:43.099
And by that I mean, there are times when you might want to consider creating batch or rendered

00:00:43.099 --> 00:00:47.599
content and publishing that to Connect instead of interactive applications.

00:00:47.599 --> 00:00:49.720
Now, I love Shiny applications.

00:00:49.720 --> 00:00:56.040
I got into working with our studio through learning Shiny, and I appreciate it very deeply.

00:00:56.040 --> 00:01:00.200
And I went through a period of my life when everything I did was a Shiny application.

00:01:00.200 --> 00:01:04.639
I'm sure lots of you can associate with that feeling.

00:01:04.639 --> 00:01:11.879
But as you learn more about the user experience that you might want to give your viewing audience,

00:01:11.879 --> 00:01:19.199
there are times when something rendered is a little bit more interesting to explore.

00:01:19.199 --> 00:01:24.720
Because not everybody wants to come to Connect every day to interact with an application.

00:01:24.720 --> 00:01:30.519
There might be times when sending something to somebody's email is a better way to reach

00:01:30.519 --> 00:01:35.839
them, to interact with them, or to update them by two changes in the content that you

00:01:35.839 --> 00:01:36.839
want to deliver.

00:01:36.839 --> 00:01:41.480
So think about the user experience that you'd like to deliver when you're thinking about

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:45.639
what type of content you want to produce and put on Connect.

00:01:45.639 --> 00:01:50.080
I love this feature in Connect because I love robotic process automation.

00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:51.400
I love automating things.

00:01:51.400 --> 00:01:52.400
It's very fun.

00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:54.639
I love scheduling content.

00:01:54.639 --> 00:01:57.000
And you can't schedule interactive content.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:02.599
You schedule something to run and render and then you can distribute it out to your audience,

00:02:02.599 --> 00:02:03.599
which is very cool.

00:02:03.599 --> 00:02:04.639
It can go out.

00:02:04.639 --> 00:02:08.320
You can create a custom email to send to them.

00:02:08.320 --> 00:02:14.639
And then everybody who you need to update about something on a set schedule can get

00:02:14.639 --> 00:02:17.000
that update.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:19.440
And that's very nice.

00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:27.399
But you might have experienced this when you start to move beyond scheduling a single thing

00:02:27.399 --> 00:02:33.039
and there are suddenly multiple things that have dependencies on each other.

00:02:33.039 --> 00:02:38.559
You might get in this situation, which is an actual project I did and put on Connect

00:02:38.559 --> 00:02:42.479
where I have a number of our Markdown documents that need to run.

00:02:42.479 --> 00:02:47.520
One runs at 3 a.m., one runs at 4 a.m., one runs at 5 a.m.

00:02:47.520 --> 00:02:54.279
By 6 a.m., if everything has run correctly and ended on time and everything, depending

00:02:54.279 --> 00:02:59.800
on the previous thing, is all going correctly and ran without an error, you should get an

00:02:59.800 --> 00:03:02.800
email in your inbox with the updated data.

00:03:03.039 --> 00:03:08.960
But if you show somebody this document, they're going to think you're unhinged.

00:03:08.960 --> 00:03:15.600
So yes, you could create workflows that have different pieces of content running at different

00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:21.240
times that get chained together in Connect and you can do this with on-base scheduling.

00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:24.279
That's not actually what you want.

00:03:24.279 --> 00:03:31.160
What you want is to be able to push that render-on-demand button programmatically with code.

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:35.360
You don't want cron-job-style rendering all the time.

00:03:35.360 --> 00:03:37.440
Sometimes you want event-style rendering.

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:42.759
I want to run this report if and only if my data pipeline succeeds.

00:03:42.759 --> 00:03:45.240
I don't care what time of day that is.

00:03:45.240 --> 00:03:48.919
I just want it to run now.

00:03:48.919 --> 00:03:51.199
So this is announcement number one.

00:03:51.199 --> 00:03:56.039
Maybe you've already discovered this package out in the wild, but there's been a package

00:03:56.039 --> 00:04:00.600
that my colleagues in solutions engineering have maintained for a long time, and I want

00:04:00.600 --> 00:04:04.960
to announce that the Connect team is now taking over support and maintenance of the

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:06.839
Connect API package.

00:04:06.839 --> 00:04:14.880
It had an experimental function called variant render, which you could use to do this execute

00:04:14.880 --> 00:04:19.799
or render-on-demand style execution for content in Connect.

00:04:19.799 --> 00:04:26.160
We've replaced it with a content render function and also a content restart function, which

00:04:26.239 --> 00:04:33.239
if you're getting really wild, you can use to restart interactive content as well.

00:04:33.239 --> 00:04:36.239
That's something that you're interested in doing on demand.

00:04:36.239 --> 00:04:42.040
There are different user experience issues with that that you may experience, but it's

00:04:42.040 --> 00:04:43.880
also an option.

00:04:43.880 --> 00:04:45.839
So that's announcement number one.

00:04:45.839 --> 00:04:49.160
Announcement number two, we've done the same thing for Python.

00:04:49.160 --> 00:04:51.000
And this is actually a bigger announcement.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:56.839
We've launched a Pythonic interface for developers to work against the public APIs of Posit's

00:04:56.839 --> 00:04:59.279
professional products.

00:04:59.279 --> 00:05:01.000
And this is the unofficial logo.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:05.000
Oh, no, announcement three, new cookbook.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:07.000
Announcement four, new blog post.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:08.000
All right.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:09.000
Thank you, Kelly.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:10.000
Thank you, Kelly.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:11.000
All right.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:11.000


00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:22.000
Bye.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:23.000
Bye.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Bye.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:25.000
Bye.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:26.000
Bye.

